Banking Capstone - Data Wrangling and Stastical Analysis

Demetri Lee

December 1, 2018

Working to predict the success of bank marketing

Im working on predicting the success of telemarketing calls for a bank thats selling long-term deposits. A Portuguese retail bank was addressed, with data collected from 2008 to 2013, thus including the effects of the recent financial crisis of 2008. With 21 variables available for analysis, I hope to derive knowledge for a model that would confirm how to better focus resources towards clients with a high chance of agreeing to registering for extra banking services.

This is the data dictionary provided by the respective retail bank:

Bank client data

  1. age: numeric
  2. job: type of job (categorical: admin, blue-collar, entrepreneur, housemaid, management, retired, self-employed, services, student, technician, unemployed, unknown)
  3. marital: marital status (categorical: divorced, married, single, unknown; note: divorced means divorced or widowed)
  4. education: (categorical: basic.4y, basic.6y, basic.9y, high.school, illiterate, professional.course, university.degree, unknown)
  5. default: has credit in default? (categorical: no, yes, unknown)
  6. housing: has housing loan? (categorical: no, yes, unknown)
  7. loan: has personal loan? (categorical: no, yes, unknown)

Related with the last contact of the current campaign

  1. contact: contact communication type (categorical: cellular, telephone)
  2. month: last contact month of year (categorical: jan, feb, mar, , nov, dec)
  3. day_of_week: last contact day of the week (categorical: mon, tue, wed, thu, fri)
  4. duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric). Important note: this attribute highly affects the output target (e.g., if duration=0 then y=no). Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call y is obviously known. Thus, this input should only be included for benchmark purposes and should be discarded if the intention is to have a realistic predictive model.

Other attributes

  1. campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)
  2. pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric; 999 means client was not previously contacted)
  3. previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)
  4. poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical: failure, nonexistent, success)

Social and economic context attributes

  1. emp.var.rate: employment variation rate - quarterly indicator (numeric)
  2. cons.price.idx: consumer price index - monthly indicator (numeric)
  3. cons.conf.idx: consumer confidence index - monthly indicator (numeric)
  4. euribor3m: euribor 3 month rate - daily indicator (numeric)
  5. nr.employed: number of employees - quarterly indicator (numeric)

Output variable (desired target)

  1. y: has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: yes, no)

Data Preparation

Lets start by reading in the dataset with values delimited by semi-colons along with designated column types as indicated by the data dictionary.

bankfull <- read_delim(file = "bank-additional.csv", delim = ";", col_types = "iccccccccciiiicdddddc")

bankfull$job <- as.factor(bankfull$job)
bankfull$marital <- as.factor(bankfull$marital)
bankfull$education <- as.factor(bankfull$education)
bankfull$default <- as.factor(bankfull$default)
bankfull$housing <- as.factor(bankfull$housing)
bankfull$loan <- as.factor(bankfull$loan)
bankfull$contact <- as.factor(bankfull$contact)
bankfull$month <- as.factor(bankfull$month)
bankfull$day_of_week <- as.factor(bankfull$day_of_week)
bankfull$poutcome <- as.factor(bankfull$poutcome)
bankfull$y <- as.factor(bankfull$y)

Lets rename variables to be more descriptive and avoid use of periods.

bankfull <- rename(bankfull, duration_sec = "duration")

bankfull <- rename(bankfull, days_passed = "pdays")
bankfull <- rename(bankfull, prev_contact_cnt = "previous")
bankfull <- rename(bankfull, prev_outcome = "poutcome")

bankfull <- rename(bankfull, cons_price_idx = "cons.price.idx")
bankfull <- rename(bankfull, cons_conf_idx = "cons.conf.idx")
bankfull <- rename(bankfull, num_employed = "nr.employed")

Exploring Data with Plots

Looking at Campaign results

A cursory look at the subscribe variable will show most customers do not sign up for the extra service so the results are very skewed.

ggplot(bankfull, aes(x = subscribed, fill = subscribed)) + geom_bar() + 
  labs(title = "Subscription Counts")

The proportion of no to yes in a table:

prop.table(table(bankfull$subscribed))
## 
##        no       yes 
## 0.8905074 0.1094926

When looking for clients that have subscribed to a previous campaign there are too many nonexistent values.

ggplot(bankfull, aes(prev_outcome, fill=prev_outcome)) + geom_bar() + 
  labs(title="Subscription Count from a Previous Campaign")

When comparing clients that subscribed to the previous campaign and the current campaign, the nonexistent values become distracting.

ggplot(bankfull, aes(x=prev_outcome, fill=subscribed)) + geom_bar()

With the nonexistent values removed, notably more than half the clients can be seen as having subscribed again.

ctable(bankfull$prev_outcome, bankfull$subscribed)

bankfull_prev <- filter(bankfull, prev_outcome != "nonexistent")
ggplot(bankfull_prev, aes(x=prev_outcome, fill=subscribed)) + 
  geom_bar(position="fill") + 
  labs(title = "Proportion of subscriptions from previous campaign")

Last Contact Data

Last contact data will include details about the last contact with the client. Variables includ type of contact, the day and month of contact, and the duration of the last contact.

Regarding last contact data, it appears customers are more inclined to subscribe when contacted via cellular compared to telephone.

ggplot(bankfull, aes(x=contact_typ, fill=subscribed)) + geom_bar()

If we stack each month as relative proportions we can see customers are more receptive to subscribing in March followed by December before September.

ggplot(bankfull, aes(x=month, fill=subscribed)) + geom_bar(position="fill")

Important note: this attribute highly affects the output target (e.g., if duration=0 then subscribed=no). Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call subscribed is obviously known. Thus, this input should only be included for benchmark purposes and should be discarded if the intention is to have a realistic predictive model.

Socioeconomic Data

While generating a matrix of plots between the socioeconomic data, there looks to be a high correlation in the following 2 pairs:

  • euribor3m vs employment variation rate
  • euribor3m vs number employed at bank
# From emp_var_rate to num_employed

ggpairs(bankfull, columns=16:20, progress=FALSE)

What if I filter out the subscriptions?

Deep correlation between Employee Variation Rate and Euribor at 3 months but doesnt seem like it affects client subscriptions.

ggplot(bankfull, aes(emp_var_rate, euribor3m)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~subscribed) + geom_smooth(method=lm)

Running a scatterplot for the Employment Variation Rate versus the 3 month Euribor reiterates the correlation.

ggplot(bankfull, aes(x=emp_var_rate, y=euribor3m)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(subscribed)), alpha = 0.50, position="jitter") + 
  labs(title = "Euribor (3 months) vs Employment Variation Rate (quarterly)")

ggplot(bankfull, aes(x=cons_conf_idx, y=cons_price_idx)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=factor(subscribed), shape=factor(subscribed)), alpha=0.50, position="jitter") + 
  labs(title = "Consumer Price Index vs Consumer Confidence Index")

Using box-plots used for the employment variable rate and the 3 month Euribor rating with respect to subscriptions continue to look similar.

ggplot(bankfull, aes(x=subscribed, y=emp_var_rate, fill=subscribed)) + geom_boxplot()

ggplot(bankfull, aes(x=subscribed, y=euribor3m, fill=subscribed)) + geom_boxplot()

For this exploratory data analysis phase, here are a few conclusions:

  1. Reach out to subscribers from previous campaign as more than 50% of subscribers will re-subscribe.
  2. Contact clients via their mobile phone as the success rate is more than twice than clients contacted via a regular telephone.
  3. It is advised to close a subscription by the 11th contact because there is a strong chance of rejection.
  4. The length of the call should be more than 274 seconds or 4 min, 34 sec.

Write the revised dataset into a cleaned-up file.

write_csv(bankfull, path="bankfull_clean.csv", col_names=TRUE)
